I have a situation where I have several goroutines running concurrently, and after waiting for them all to finish, I want to know if any of them had an issue that warrants failing the transaction enclosing all of this.  The simplest and most obvious way to accomplish what I want is considered a data race by the race detector.  There are easy ways to satisfy the race detector, but I&#39;d like to make sure I understand data races and what problems I&#39;m actually solving by keeping the race detector happy.

I can&#39;t tell from reading [The Go Memory Model](https://golang.org/ref/mem) if writing the same value (`true`) to a shared `bool` from different goroutines is actually a problem.  Here&#39;s a simple example:

	package main

	import (
		&quot;fmt&quot;
		&quot;sync&quot;
	)

	func main() {
		var b bool

		var wg sync.WaitGroup
		for i := 0; i &lt; 5; i++ {
			wg.Add(1)
			go func() {
				b = true
				wg.Done()
			}()
		}
		wg.Wait()
		fmt.Println(b)
	}

The race detector complains about writing to `b` from multiple goroutines.  I can avoid the problem in many ways (channels, multiple `bool` variables, etc.), but I think I prefer setting up with:

	var once sync.Once
	btrue := func() {
		b = true
	}

and then replacing `b = true` with `once.Do(btrue)`.

But I want to know if the na&#239;ve approach is actually problematic, or if the race detector simply always complains about concurrent writes, even if they are actually safe in a given situation.

I think I understand many of the problems that could arise if `b` were read before `wg.Wait()`, or if different goroutines might try to write different values.  But in this case `b` is initially zero-valued (`false`), and then multiple goroutines attempt setting it to the same value, then we have a synchronization event (`wg.Wait()`), and then we read `b` to see if it got changed.  In my actual program, zero, one, or several goroutines may try to set the `bool` to `true` (depending on if any failure conditions arise), and the whole point is to see if *any* set it to `true`.  It is never set to `false` by any of the goroutines.  It&#39;s either been written to zero times (so still zero-valued/`false`) or more than zero times (so now `true`).

Is there anything that could actually go wrong?  All I can think of is if for some reason the compiler were to emit code that *does* try to read `b` rather than blindly setting it.  If it tried an approach of conditionally flipping it to `true` by reading it, and only setting it to `true` if it wasn&#39;t already `true`, then of course we&#39;d be in a normal data-race scenario.

I&#39;m happy to appease the race detector, but I want to make sure I understand the issues.  Doing a lot of reading around, I think perhaps the answer is that this is technically a data race (unprotected writes), and that&#39;s what the race detector is complaining about.  But perhaps it isn&#39;t a *race condition*, meaning perhaps this is perfectly sound, despite (maybe?) being technically a data race?

